## ğŸ“Œ Basic Concepts

Every file and directory in Linux has three permission categories:

- **User (u)**: Owner of the file
- **Group (g)**: Group associated with the file
- **Others (o)**: Everyone else

Each category has three permissions:
- **r** â€“ read
- **w** â€“ write
- **x** â€“ execute

### Example:
```bash
-rwxr-xr-- 1 user group 1234 Jan 1 12:00 example.sh
chmod â€“ Change permissions
chmod 755 file.txt      # rwxr-xr-x
chmod u+x script.sh     # Add execute for user
chmod go-w file.txt     # Remove write for group & others
chown â€“ Change file owner/group 
chown user:group file.txt
chgrp â€“ Change group chgrp groupname file.txt
ğŸ§ª Special Permissions

ğŸ“ SetUID (s)
	â€¢	Executes the file as the fileâ€™s owner
chmod u+s script.sh
ğŸ“ SetGID (s)
	â€¢	Executes as group OR new files inherit the group
chmod g+s directory/
ğŸ“ Sticky Bit (t)
	â€¢	On directories: Only owner can delete their files
chmod +t /tmp
ğŸ” Viewing Permissions
ls -l                # View permission string
stat file.txt        # Detailed metadata
ğŸ—‚ ACLs â€“ Access Control Lists
setfacl -m u:john:rwx file.txt
getfacl file.txt
ğŸ§  Tips for Remembering
	â€¢	Use ls -l often to build familiarity.
	â€¢	Practice changing and breaking permissions in a test directory.
	â€¢	Understand the numeric values:
	â€¢	r=4, w=2, x=1
	â€¢	So chmod 754 = rwxr-xr--

