ğŸš« Prevent Directory Listing (Security Trick)

If you want people to access files only if they know the exact filename but not list them:
chmod 701 private_dir
ğŸ“Œ View Permissions Recursively

To list all files and their permissions under a directory:
find . -type f -exec ls -l {} \;
find / -type f -perm -002 2>/dev/null

ğŸ”’ Tighten Down Files

Lock down a file so only the owner can read/write: chmod 600 secrets.txt

chmod -R 755 my_project/
chown -R sa:shell my_project/
ğŸ§  Hidden Insights
	â€¢	You can mix numeric and symbolic methods across scripts.
	â€¢	Always double-check permissions with stat or ls -l before and after changes.
	â€¢	Sticky bits are common in /tmp or shared group folders to avoid accidental deletions.
	â€¢	On modern Linux systems, ACLs (Access Control Lists) may override traditional permissions. Use getfacl and setfacl for those cases.

